HISTORY OF ASSUMPTION OF COMMAND
THE CEREMONY YOU ARE ABOUT TO WITNESS IS DEEPLY
ROOTED IN MILITARY TRADITION AND DATES BACK TO THE
TIME OF FREDERICK THE GREAT OF PRUSSIA. DURING THAT
PERIOD, MILITARY ORGANIZATIONS DEVELOPED FLAGS BEAR-
ING SPECIALIZED COLORS AND DESIGNS UNIQUE TO THEM.
WHEN SOLDIERS FOLLOWED THEIR LEADERS INTO BATTLE,
THEY KEPT SIGHT OF THESE FLAGS. IF A BANNER STILL
WAVED AFTER THE CONFLICT, IT WAS A SIGN THAT THEIR
SIDE WAS VICTORIOUS ON THE BATTLEFIELD. BECAUSE OF
ITS SYMBOLIC IMPORTANCE, THE FLAG WAS INCORPORATED
INTO THE ASSUMPTION OF COMMAND CEREMONY. THE
ORGANIZATIONAL BANNER WAS EXCHANGED IN PUBLIC FOR
ALL TO WITNESS THE NAMING OF THE NEW SOVEREIGN
LEADER OF ANY ARMY. THE MODERN CEREMONY IS SIMPLE
AND DIRECT, YET CONTINUES TO ANNOUNCE TO ALL THE
AUTHORITY OF THE INCOMING COMMANDER IN THE FINEST
OF MILITARY TRADITIONS.

COLONEL DAMON
DALBY
Colonel Timothy (Damon) Dalby is the Commander of the
17th Mission Support Group, Goodfellow Air Force Base,
Texas. The Group consists of six squadrons delivering securi-
ty, communications, logistics, civil engineering, contracting,
human resources and community support programs for the
bases 14,000 joint service, retirees, and family members.
Colonel Dalby oversees
$1.2 billion in real property, equipment, supplies, $38 million
in government contracts, and an operational budget of $41
million to facilitate the Department of Defense's premiere joint
intelligence schoolhouse and joint firefighter academy. His
group sustains the Air Forces largest sensitive compartment-
ed information facility complex, the $46 million Louis F.
Garland Joint Fire Protection Training Academy, 3,600 dormi-
tory rooms, 300 lodging rooms, and a food service program
generating over 1 million meals per year. Additionally, his
team maintains the largest SIPR network in Air Education and
Training Command and the largest fire truck fleet in the Air
Force.
Prior to this assignment, he has served in various positions as
a Civil Engineer at base, Numbered Air Force, Combatant
Command and Air Staff levels, as well as RED HORSE. He
served as Squadron Commander two times and deployed five
times to Iraq, Afghanistan, Qatar, Kuwait, and the Horn of
Africa.
Col Dalby is from Grosse Pointe, Michigan. He was commis-
sioned through the Reserved Officer Training Corps upon
graduation from Michigan State University in May 2001. He is
married to Alison, and they have a son Nolan.

Major Alan D. Geason is a student graduate of Air
Command and Staff College at Maxwell Air Force
Base, Alabama. Prior to this assignment, Major
Geason served as the Director of Operations for the
707th Communications Squadron, 707th Intelligence,
Surveillance, and Reconnaissance Group, 70th Intelli-
gence, Surveillance, and Reconnaissance Wing, Fort
Meade, Maryland. He was responsible for coordina-
tion of communications and information services to
support the 70th Intelligence, Surveillance and Re-
connaissance Wings cryptologic mission. Additionally,
the squadron provided timely and reliable secure
communications, conducted cyberspace operations,
and provided cyber program management to warf-
ighters and cryptologic operations around the globe.
Major Geason was commissioned as a second lieuten-
ant in May 2011 from Bowling Green State University
Detachment 620 Reserve Officer Training Corp and
has spent 13 years on Active Duty. Major Geasons
past duty locations include Osan Air Base, Republic of
Korea, Hickam Air Force Base, Hawaii, the Office of
the Director of National Intelligence, Tysons Corner,
Virginia, Eielson Air Force Base, Alaska, and Fort
Meade, Maryland.
Major Geason is from Sandusky, Ohio. He was
commissioned through Reserved Officer Training Corps
Detachment 620 upon graduation form the University of
Toledo in May 2011. He is married to Aleah and they have
three children - Ava, Alan III, and Adalynne.
